## Current build posture

The live build standard is explicitly **Alpha / Graybox pedagogy-first**.

That means:

- quest artifacts should be plain and technical
- almost all flavor text should be removed during active build
- learning goals must be visible without themed framing
- question curation should be explicit
- exit standards should be observable
- the quest should stay small enough to revise quickly
- the quest should help real prep more than it helps presentation

Interpretation rule:

Do not confuse “lighter quest” with “weaker quest.”

The quest is intentionally smaller so the educational object stays visible.

---

## Quest philosophy

A quest is a prep container.

Its job is to make the learning target legible and actionable.

A strong quest should answer:

- what is this quest trying to teach?
- which questions best map to those goals?
- which reps are proving reps?
- which optional harder reps are useful stretch work?
- what does honest completion look like?
- where should reflection on the work be captured?

A quest is **not**:

- a flavor wrapper
- a room-by-room dungeon page
- a giant bundle of vaguely related problems
- a duplicate of the skill note
- a disguised archive
- or a generic checklist with no teaching logic

Interpretation rule:

If the quest looks interesting but does not make the educational object clearer, it is weak.

---

## Relationship between note and quest

### Skill / Pattern Note

The skill note teaches:

- what the pattern is
- how to recognize it
- what it does well
- what it does not do
- and how its mechanics branch into meaningful variants

The quest should link to the note.
It should not duplicate it.

### Quest

The quest turns that educational foundation into actual prep structure.

The quest should own:

- learning goals
- representative questions
- proving reps
- optional harder reps
- exit signals
- quest-log support

Interpretation rule:

The note teaches the pattern.
The quest teaches what to do with it.

---

## Core quest template

During the current phase, a quest should generally include:

1. Quest Name
2. Purpose
3. Learning Goals
4. Linked Skill / Pattern Note
5. Representative Questions
6. Interview-Quality Questions
7. Optional Harder Reps
8. Exit Signals
9. Quest Log / Work Diary
10. Notes Status
11. Curation Concerns

That is enough.

Do not add more structure unless it materially improves learning or execution.

---

## Section standards

### 1. Quest Name

Keep the name stable and clear.

The name should identify the actual educational object cleanly.

In the current build phase, clarity beats flavor.

---

### 2. Purpose

This section should answer:

- why this quest exists
- what kind of capability it is trying to build
- why it matters in interview prep

Keep this short and technical.

A good purpose section should orient the learner without slipping into worldbuilding or note duplication.

---

### 3. Learning Goals

This is one of the most important sections in the quest.

Learning goals should answer:

- what the learner should understand by the end
- what kinds of problem-solving behavior should improve
- what kind of articulation should be possible after the quest

Good learning goals are:

- specific
- mechanic-facing
- observable
- useful for question curation later

Bad learning goals are:

- vague
- quota-based
- prestige-driven
- or just restating the quest name

Interpretation rule:

If the learning goals are weak, the question set will usually be weak too.

---

### 4. Linked Skill / Pattern Note

This section should include:

- the linked note title
- a short line on why that note matters for this quest

Do not paste the note into the quest.

The note exists to provide the educational foundation.
The quest exists to turn that foundation into actual reps and standards.

---

### 5. Representative Questions

This section answers:

> what questions best map to the quest’s learning goals?

This is the first curation layer.

These questions should be chosen because they are strong educational fits for the goals, not because they are simply famous or convenient.

For each question, capture at least:

- title
- source label / number
- why it belongs here
- what goal or mechanic it serves

Interpretation rule:

Representative questions are not automatically the proving set.
Their first job is to map the learning territory clearly.

---

### 6. Interview-Quality Questions

This section answers:

> which questions should the learner be able to solve and explain at real interview quality for this quest?

This is the main proving-rep section.

These questions should be:

- representative
- high-signal
- non-redundant
- strong enough to test real understanding

For each question, capture at least:

- title
- source label / number
- why it is in the proving set
- which learning goal(s) it proves
- whether it assumes any prerequisite skill beyond the quest’s core mechanic

Interpretation rule:

Do not let “interview-quality” become a synonym for “hard.”
The question should prove the quest’s move, not just create suffering.

---

### 7. Optional Harder Reps

This section answers:

> what questions stretch the quest, combine it with another mechanic, or test deeper judgment?

These are optional.

They should be included only when they are genuinely relevant and educationally useful.

For each harder rep, capture at least:

- title
- source label / number
- why it is harder
- what extra prerequisite it may assume
- why it is still relevant rather than random

Helpful phrasing:

- also needs understanding of pattern X
- also leans on heap / graph / sliding window / prefix sum / etc.
- adds stronger implementation pressure
- adds disguise or mixed-mechanic reasoning

Interpretation rule:

Optional harder reps should deepen the quest, not bloat it.

---

### 8. Exit Signals

This section defines what must be true to move on honestly.

Exit signals should be:

- observable
- tied to the learning goals
- clear enough to reduce self-negotiation
- restrained enough to avoid quota theater

Good exit signals usually include things like:

- can explain the core mechanic cleanly
- can justify the representation
- can distinguish this quest from nearby false friends
- can solve the proving reps with interview structure
- can articulate where the move breaks or hands off to another pattern

Bad exit signals include things like:

- “feels ready”
- “seems comfortable”
- “probably gets it”
- giant hidden quotas
- arbitrary repetition targets with no educational reason

Interpretation rule:

Exit signals should protect against fake clears without turning the quest into an anxiety ritual.

---

### 9. Quest Log / Work Diary

Every quest should include a quest-log section or quest-log link.

The quest log is the technical reflection artifact for the work.

Its job is to record:

- what was attempted
- what was cleared
- where execution broke
- what kind of blocker it was
- what should happen next

The quest log should support real work reflection, not flavor writing.

Keep it practical.

---

### 10. Notes Status

This section should briefly state:

- linked note status
- quest status
- whether curation is still provisional
- whether later refinement is expected

This helps prevent false completeness.

---

### 11. Curation Concerns

This section should track the main open curation questions.

Examples:

- whether a question is the right representative fit
- whether a proving rep is too redundant
- whether a harder rep is actually relevant
- whether a nearby mechanic is muddying the quest boundary

Keep this short and useful.

---

## Question-capture standard

For any question included in a quest, capture at least:

- title
- source label / number
- why it belongs
- what mechanic, disguise, or learning goal it maps to
- whether it is representative, proving, or optional harder work
- prerequisite skills if it assumes knowledge outside the core quest

This is the minimum useful curation standard.

Do not let question lists become raw lists with no reasoning.

---

## What stays out of the quest in this phase

During the current Alpha / Graybox phase, keep these out of the quest:

- room-by-room themed structure
- Canonical Enemies / Elite Variants / Boss Chamber presentation as the primary build layer
- full skill-note duplication
- long flavor sections
- giant reserve pools
- full solution archives
- code dumps
- broad region summaries
- active project-state tracking
- historical rationale for every choice

These may exist conceptually in the larger campaign model, but they should not drive active artifact production right now.

Interpretation rule:

If a section mainly serves presentation instead of pedagogy, cut it.

---

## Depth and compression rules

### Good compression

- keeps the quest small and usable
- preserves the learning goals
- preserves the reasoning behind the question set
- keeps exit signals visible
- makes revision faster without hollowing out the quest

### Bad compression

- leaves only a list of problems
- hides the learning goals
- removes why each question belongs
- turns exit signals into vague slogans
- makes the quest too thin to guide real prep

### Good detail

- clarifies why the quest exists
- strengthens question selection
- sharpens the proving set
- reduces ambiguity about honest completion
- improves the quality of later reps

### Bad detail

- bloats the quest with decorative structure
- preserves themed sections that are not helping
- duplicates the note
- adds many problem lists with overlapping jobs
- turns the quest into a mini textbook

---

## Refinement workflow

Use a staged approach instead of trying to fully perfect every quest immediately.

### Skeleton

- quest name is clear
- purpose exists
- learning goals exist
- linked note is clear
- representative questions are selected
- interview-quality questions are selected or mostly selected
- exit signals exist
- quest log exists or is linked
- curation concerns are visible

### Stable

- learning goals are strong
- question mapping is trustworthy
- proving set is coherent
- optional harder reps are relevant
- exit signals are observable
- obvious bloat is removed

### Refined

- wording is clean
- question selection is strong
- boundaries with nearby quests are sharper
- exit signals are tighter
- the quest supports repeated real use without confusion

Current project rule:

Do **not** try to fully polish every quest before the educational foundation and question mapping are trustworthy.

---

## Common failure modes to guard against

- the quest becomes a themed wrapper instead of a prep container
- the quest duplicates the note
- learning goals are vague
- representative questions are just famous problems rather than good fits
- interview-quality questions are redundant or weak
- optional harder reps are random suffering
- exit signals are vague
- curation concerns are hidden instead of acknowledged
- the quest becomes prettier than it is useful

---

## Final interpretation rule

The standard is not:

- maximum flavor
- maximum problem volume
- maximum structure
- or maximum polish

The standard is:

a small, technically clear prep container that makes the learning goals visible, the question curation trustworthy, and the exit standard honest.
